an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Sybilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sibilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sybille","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Sybil</b> ."]},{"name":"Sibella","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":32,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":63,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sybil de Thirkelby was born about 1227, in Thirkleby, North Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Walter Thirkelby and Cecily of Thirkelby. She married Robert Salvain I about 1248, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died after 1294, in North Duffield, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"about 1227–after 1294":"umbes 1227–pärast 1294","1227–1294":"1227–1294","–1270":"–1270","1226–1300":"1226–1300","1250–1320":"1250–1320","1262–1281":"1262–1281","–Male":"Surnud","1205–1289":"1205–1289","1262":"1262","1250":"1250","1294":"1294","1281":"1281","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1205":"1205","1227":"1227","1259":"1259","1226":"1226","1289":"1289","1300":"1300","about 1248":"umbes 1248","about 1227":"umbes 1227","1320":"1320","after 1294":"pärast 1294","between 1250 and 1260":"1250 kuni 1260","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Low Moor, Yorkshire, England":"Low Moor, Yorkshire, England","North Duffield, Yorkshire, England":"North Duffield, Yorkshire, England","Thirkelby, Yorkshire, England":"Thirkleby, Yorkshire, England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Harswell, Yorkshire, England":"Harswell, Yorks